{{Infobox food | name = Belgian waffles | image = Waffle with strawberries and confectioner's sugar.jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = A Belgian waffle with [[strawberries]] and [[confectioner's sugar]] | alternate_name = | country = [[Belgium]] | region = | creator = Maurice Vermersch | type = [[Waffle]] | served = | main_ingredient = [[Flour]], [[sugar]], [[baking powder]], [[Egg (food)|eggs]], [[milk]], [[butter]] | variations = [[Chocolate chip]], [[blueberry]], [[strawberry]], [[Nutella]], etc. | calories = | other = }}
In North America, '''Belgian waffles''' are a variety of [[waffle]] with a lighter batter, larger squares, and deeper pockets than ordinary American waffles. Belgian waffles were originally leavened with [[Baker's yeast|yeast]], but [[baking powder]] is now often used.<ref name="Roberts" /> They are often eaten as a [[breakfast]] food; toppings vary from whipped cream, confectioners sugar, soft fruit, and [[chocolate]] spread, to syrup and butter or [[margarine]]. They may also be served with vanilla ice cream and fresh fruit (such as strawberries) as a [[dessert]].
In [[Belgium]] itself, there are several kinds of waffle, including the [[Waffle#Varieties|Brussels waffle]] and the [[Waffle#Varieties|Liège waffle]].
==History== [[File:Worlds Fair - Belgian Village (4626896426).jpg|thumb|upright|float|right|The Belgian Village at the [[1964 New York World's Fair]], where the waffles were popularized]] Originally showcased in 1958<ref name="CooksInfo" /> at [[Expo 58]] in [[Brussels]], Belgian waffles were introduced to North America by a Belgian named Walter Cleyman at the [[Century 21 Exposition]] in [[Seattle]] in 1962, and served with [[whipped cream]] and strawberries.<ref>{{cite news| title= There's Something for All at Seattle's Fair| work= [[Spokane Daily Chronicle]] | date= April 24, 1962| url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=C8NWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VfcDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6881%2C6359287 |page= 2| via= Google News Archive| access-date= }}</ref> The waffles were further popularized in the United States during the [[1964 New York World's Fair]]<ref name="Roberts">{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/27/nyregion/thecity/27read.html |title= A Fair, a Law and the Urban Walker |last=Roberts|first=Sam| work= [[The New York Times]] |accessdate=2009-03-19 | date=2008-07-27| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131113114709/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/27/nyregion/thecity/27read.html| archivedate=November 13, 2013 | deadurl= no}}</ref> at [[Flushing Meadows Park]] in [[Queens]], [[New York City]]. These waffles were introduced by Maurice Vermersch of [[Brussels]], Belgium.{{cn|date= July 2018}} Largely based on a simplified recipe for the Brussels waffles, Vermersch decided to change the name to the Bel-Gem Waffle upon observing that many Americans could not correctly identify Brussels as the capital of Belgium.<ref name="Newsday">{{cite news|title=His waffles made memories at the Queens World's Fair| date= 1989-08-22| work= [[Newsday]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DOJMAgAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA554 |title= Waffles | page= 554| work= The Oxford Encyclopedia of Food and Drink in America |via=[[Google Books]] |year= 2013 |first= Bruce| last= Kraig| |accessdate=2014-02-10}}</ref> These waffles were served with whipped cream and strawberries, and they were sold for a dollar.<ref name="CooksInfo">{{cite web| url= http://www.cooksinfo.com/belgian-waffles|title=Belgian Waffles| work= CooksInfo.com |accessdate=2009-03-19}}</ref>
