A '''diplomatic flag''' is a flag used by a [[sovereign state]] engaging in [[diplomacy]] which is different from the nation's normal [[national flag]]. Some nations also have personal flags that are used by their diplomatic representatives, such as the [[Diplomatic_flag#United_States_of_America|U.S. Foreign Service flags]].<ref>[https://flagspot.net/flags/us_dip.html Flags of the World: Diplomatic and Consular Flags (U.S.)]</ref>

==National Diplomatic Flag==
Currently, only two nations use diplomatic flags: [[Thailand]] (formerly Siam) and the [[United Kingdom]]. Different flags are used based upon the [[diplomatic rank]] of the mission. British [[High Commissioner (Commonwealth)|High Commissions]] do not use diplomatic flags but rather the normal [[flag of the United Kingdom]], since members of the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] are not considered 'foreign' by the [[government of the United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite|title=The Palgrave Macmillan Dictionary of Diplomacy|year=2012|page=104|first1=G R|last1=Berridge|first2=Lorna|last2=Lloyd|edition=3rd|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan}}</ref>

