{{Infobox organization |name = Royal Danish Academy of Sciences and Letters |image = Royal Danish Academy of Sciences and Letters seal.svg |size = 200px |motto = |formation = {{start date and age|1742}} |headquarters = [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]] |leader_title = President |leader_name = [[Kirsten Hastrup]] |membership = |website = {{URL|www.royalacademy.dk}} }}
The '''Royal Danish Academy of Sciences and Letters''' ({{lang-da|Kongelige Danske Videnskabernes Selskab}}) is a Danish non-governmental science [[Academy]], founded in 1742 for the advancement of science in Denmark. It is based in the [[Carlsberg Foundation]]'s building at the corner of [[H. C. Andersens Boulevard]] and [[Dantes Plads]] in central [[Copenhagen]].
== History == [[File:PS Krøyer - Videnskabernes Selskab.jpg|thumb|200px|left|Krøyer's painting in the Old Meeting Hall.]] The Society was founded on [[1742 in Denmark|13 November 1742]] by permission of King [[Christian VI of Denmark|Christian VI]], as a historical [[Collegium (disambiguation)|Collegium]] Antiquitatum. It was founded by secretary of state, Count [[Johan Ludvig Holstein]] and the history professor [[Hans Gram (historian)|Hans Gram]].
== Building == [[File:Carlsbergfondet.JPG|thumb|200px|The building on H.C. Andersens Boulevard.]] The building at 35 [[H. C. Andersens Boulevard]] was designed by [[Vilhelm Petersen]] in a [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical]] style.
The Carlsberg Foundation is based in the ground floor while the Royal Academy has the three upper floors. First floor contains the Old Meeting Hall, where the Academy hold their meetings. It is decorated with a large oil painting by [[Peder Severin Krøyer]] depicting ''A meeting in the Royal Scientific Society''. There is also a library and rooms for researchers. Second floor contain the Academy's secretariate and archives as the President's, General Secretary's and Editor's offices.Third floor now contains New Meeting Room. It was created in the former attic and book storage in connection with an adaption of the building in 1976. Since 2009, it has access to a roof terrace.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carlsbergfondet.dk/da/Kontakt/Bygningen.aspx|title=Bygningen|language=Danish|publisher=Carlsberg Foundation|accessdate=2013-07-19}}</ref>
==Members== Members of the Academy are researching, lecturing and publishing in nearly all fields of science. The Academy has approximately 250 national and 260 foreign members. In 2011 the division [[The Young Academy]] was added, which currently counts 34 young researchers as members<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youngacademy.dk/da/Medlemmer.aspx|title=DUA|language=Danish|publisher=DUA|accessdate=2017-09-22}}</ref>.
